## Click-to-Edit (CMS Edit Mode)

This site supports a **click-to-edit** feature. When the HAYC CMS opens the site in the iframe and the admin enables "Edit Mode", clicking any text element in the site opens the corresponding field in the CMS sidebar.

### How it works
- `useHayc()` exposes a `cp(path: string)` helper
- Spread `{...cp('configKey.fieldName')}` on any JSX element whose text comes from config
- In edit mode, clicking that element sends a `HAYC_FIELD_FOCUS` message to the CMS parent, which opens the correct sidebar section and highlights the field
- In edit mode, ALL clicks are intercepted — navigation and button actions are blocked so the admin can click freely without triggering routes

### Rule: spread cp() on every element that renders config text

The path must exactly match the config key path used in `t()` or `img()`:

```tsx
// ❌ Wrong — no cp(), click-to-edit won't work for this element
<h1>{t(config.heroConfig.mainTitle)}</h1>

// ✅ Correct — cp() path mirrors the config key used in t()
<h1 {...cp('heroConfig.mainTitle')}>{t(config.heroConfig.mainTitle)}</h1>
```

### Path convention
The path is always `configObjectName.fieldName`, matching the exact keys in `config.ts`:

```tsx
// Navigation
<span {...cp('navigationConfig.brandName')}>{t(config.navigationConfig.brandName)}</span>
<a {...cp('navigationConfig.bookViewingLink')}>{t(config.navigationConfig.bookViewingLink)}</a>

// Hero
<h1 {...cp('heroConfig.mainTitle')}>{t(config.heroConfig.mainTitle)}</h1>
<p {...cp('heroConfig.subtitle')}>{t(config.heroConfig.subtitle)}</p>
<button {...cp('heroConfig.requestTourButton')}>{t(config.heroConfig.requestTourButton)}</button>

// Nested / array fields
<p {...cp('faqConfig.items.0.question')}>{t(config.faqConfig.items[0].question)}</p>
```

### What cp() returns
- **Edit mode OFF:** `{}` — no effect on the element whatsoever
- **Edit mode ON:** `{ 'data-config-path': path, onClick: ..., style: { cursor: 'pointer' } }`

So spreading `{...cp(...)}` is always safe — it has zero effect when not in edit mode.

### When adding a new section or component
For every new component that renders config text:
1. Destructure `cp` from `useHayc()` alongside `t`, `img`, `config`
2. Add `{...cp('sectionConfig.fieldName')}` to every element that renders a config value
3. The path must be the first-level config key + field name, matching exactly what you pass to `t()`

